==== B - their literature __requires__ that sacrifice be a purely __symbolic__ gesture ~-~- thus, their sacrifice could stand in for __anything __~-~- there is nothing which is not already in the moment of sacrificing ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**__Botey &amp;#39;9__** Marianna, The Infection, Vol. 5 &amp;#34; Toward a critique of sacrificial reason: Necropolitics and radical aesthetics in Mexico&amp;#34; June

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
http:~/~/www.des-bordes.net/0.5/en/la%20infeccion/mariana_botey.html

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__The critical task of upsetting__**(%%), unraveling and unfastening (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__the //neutralization// of the power of death __**(%%)**__as a__** cultural-social **__device of control__** and political engineering, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__separates__** (%%)these forms of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__aesthetic practice from__** (%%)the realm of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__sublimatory codes__** (%%)through which capitalism used art as a toolbox to expropriate and expand over (colonize) the psychic territories attributed to “the savage, barbarian, infantile, primitive and demented.” A deconstruction of the protocols of colonial warfare and colonial narratives emerges by making evident a concealed sacrificial trace implied in modern capitalism. Moreover, the trace is activated and manifests as a political phenomenon that unfolds in the violent and brutal reality of (ex)colonial territories. Thus, we could argue that a post-colonial set of problems underlines the artistic procedure making reason unstable, displacing its centrality as an organizing axiom, and doing so by bringing into play other categories such as death, expenditure, and the concealed pulsations of the libidinal economy: that is, explicitly, by underpinning the inscription of sacrifice as central to a mapping of the human. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__The reading that interests us would emphasize the allegorical character of this __**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)**__inscription—__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)**__the inscription of //Sacrifice// as the very notion from which to operate the chain of discursive displacement in which death, ritual, politics, metaphysics and aesthetics sediment a different logic: another economy, non-economy__**(%%), a general economy. The critical task marks the extent to which the notion of sacrifice suffers an intrinsic indetermination in its multiple manifestations, working simultaneously as: theoretical operative (device-//dispositif//), historical structure, concept-metaphor, ideological device, symbolic economy, archeological evidence, juridical foundation of the state, the “secret” grammar of power and, also, a counter-image (hieroglyph) for a project of total revolt (i.e. the dismantling of the order of representation-domination). These examples come exclusively from the realm of art and its discourse (although all of them have heterogeneous correlates in the sphere of politics and the archive of history). Perhaps because the character —at once concealed and folded— of the problem of sacrifice as the //repressed representative //operating within instrumental reason has displaced its clear formulation (enunciation) as precisely a form of articulation that manifests mostly as (a) program(s) for a kind of radical aesthetics. The theoretical speculations of Bataille about the sacrificial order of the Aztecs; the analogous conceptualization Artaud proposed in the //Theater of Cruelty//—which was also propelled by an imagination of the mythic and ritual dimensions of indigenous culture; the initiatic pedagogy rehearsed by Jodorowsky in his //Panic Theater// and his early psycho-magical experiments with cinema; or the gestures of sexual transgression, perverted play and poetic violence that crisscross the multiple lexical and formal experiments of Gurrola, participate in a discontinuous and intermittent movement that approaches this other non-economy or sacrificial economy.&amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;_ftnref4&amp;#34;/}}(% style=&amp;#34;color:blue&amp;#34; %)^^(5)^^url:http://www.des-bordes.net/0.5/en/la%20infeccion/mariana_botey.html#_ftn4(%%) The contemporary practice of Margolles emerges in the multiple planes of circulation of these estranged and un-folded (doubled) figures, a diagram of a field of forces that forms and limits the contemporary: a cartography for a de-sublimated modernity, recounting an orgy of violent representations, while at the same time dismantling them, and searching for a space that overflows into (or is expended as) pure manifestation.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== C - vote negative ~-~- their plan is a meaningless fig-leaf for their discussion of sacrifice that has zero relation to either production incentives or production restrictions ~-~- makes the aff impossible to debate ====</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Michigan/pages/Allen-Pappas%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/19"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Michigan/pages/Allen-Pappas%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/19/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Michigan.Allen-Pappas Neg:e239ef86-0f97-4504-8e97-f4ab7af08602</id><guid>e239ef86-0f97-4504-8e97-f4ab7af08602</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Michigan.Allen-Pappas Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Michigan</space><pageName>Allen-Pappas Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>19</number><headline>==== The logic of sacrifice and the aesthetic of excess in the 1ac credits the symoblic order with tremendous powers ~-~- this sacrifice ultimately re-trenches into another form of exchange; sacrifice in exchange for the end of rationalist, production-logic ~-~- we should reject this blackmail as an __intolerable sacrifice__ against which we can imagine a cessation of production-logic through __affective sharing__ that allows us to avoid the trap of libidinal liberation.  They do not have a reason why expenditure and sacrifice are necessary to sharing ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**__Verwoert &amp;#39;12__** ~-~- Access Date, Jan Verwoert is an art critic based in Berlin. He is a contributing editor to Frieze magazine and also writes regularly about contemporary art for such art magazines as Afterall, Metropolis M. Teaches at the MA Fine Arts department at the Piet Zwart Institute Rotterdam. http:~/~/www.artandeducation.net/announcement/jan-verwoert-last-lecture/

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
Beyond voicing this distaste for the merely strategical, the critique in the previous couple of talks concentrated increasingly on the fact that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__any symbolic order__ (%%)(the art world in particular) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__is __(%%)__always (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)also a //sacrificial economy//. So the inscription into the symbolic(%%) therefore (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)seems to (%%)imply, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)demand (%%)and retroactively justify (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a sacrifice(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)(e.g. your life for your career). (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__But this is intolerable. __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__So __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__perhaps the strongest reason for the critique of a false belief in the symbolic order is the impulse to reject the imposed need for an intolerable sacrifice__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__. The dream of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__exiting the symbolic order altogether, however, seems __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__an __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__impossible fantasy__(%%), as, in the arts, we arrive as arrivistes in the field of the other—f(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__acing expectations, desiring the recognition of our desires and materially depending on it.__(%%) Still, suspended on the threshold of the symbolic, on the rim of this regimented field, in a material zone where non-sense makes too much sense, the question remains whether we cannot discover something moving—motions, things, creatures, ideas that will not be sacrificed but will stay alive and wiggling, moving in their erratic motion: motives that move things, souls and thoughts, like //locomotives//—always //un poco loco//—throughout the history of art and philosophy. __To delineate and develop__ some such __locomotives in order to open up a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)counter-discourse to the sacrifical logic (%%)of the symbolic order—on its threshold—(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)was the desire that first led us to look at motives (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)related to the production(% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) of(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)the effect/(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__affect__(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)of art. Discussing the //motivations// for production, the attempt was to try and replace the vocabulary of the strategical paradigm—the lingo of declared intentions and the cocksure construction of references—with more shaky terms like //inspiration//, //vocation// and //dedication//: terms that, precisely because of their existential dimension, exist on the threshold of the unverifiable, and therefore always remain riddled by Iron Maiden’s tormenting question “How can I be sure that what I saw last night was real and not just fantasy?” (Orpheus tried to check and he blew it.) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__In pursuit of the notion of dedication, the question of //care// as the ulimate existential motivation (__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__Why do we do what we do? ‘Cos we care.) __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__was raised, exposing its ambivalent position on the threshold of the symbolic: always drawn into a symbolic economy of tit for tat, care still remains unconditional and therefore excessive, empowered by the need of the other__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__,__(%%) and, precisely because of this, always deprived of a safe symbolic mandate, since the nature of the other remains fundamentally indeterminable. For who would know what anyone really needed? On this limit of acknowledging the missing mandate, the locomotif of a creature appeared in the history of painting: the lion that walked into St. Jerome’s study one day, thorn in paw. Jerome, being a translator, no certified cat-doctor, unprepared and without symbolic mandate, plucked the thorn anyway, intiating a social mode of conviviality with the wild cat without a contract, economy or grand narrative to symbolically validate it. The only reason for this being possible was perhaps that his study (as Antonello da Messina and Vincenzo Catena depict it) was a semi-public space, open to the occurence of such events. Animals then continued to linger on the threshold of the symbolic, as creatures that wiggle, that embody the motion of emotion and the effect of affect on the soul, as witnesses to this effect in ways that are not entirely reducable to symbolic signification. This final talk will try to substantiate this intuition further by looking at the locomotif of Orpheus and the animals which continued through the centuries to manifest intuitions about the affective effect of art and the kind of creaturely social bond it may initiate. As the muse Kaliope’s child, the figure of Orpheus may aso bring us back to the question of inspiration as (demonic) amusement in the society of the muses (the museum as pan-demonium). (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__In defiance of the sacrifice __(%%)__of affect (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to the symbolic, another motif which emerged was that of a particular face(%%): the appeal of a face that generates emotions as material events, (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a face that cannot be consecrated to the symbolic laws of social value: (%%)the shitface, the profane face, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)neither good nor bad but in touch(%%) with—(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and sharing(%%)—the devine through touching the soul__, profanely. As a practice, profanation, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__the sharing __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__of the material share __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__in the ritual of veneration __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__(the holy body, the host, that which becomes edible) __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__may __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__then finally __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__emerge as the model for a mode of __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__art and __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__thinking that could allow us to move along the threshold to the symbolic, sharing materially instead of sacrificing symbolically __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__what is divine and secret.__(%%) To further exemplify this intuition of sharing through profanation, two more locomotifs will be invoked: the Sicillian custom of eating Santa Lucia’s eyes and the incredible pleasure of looking at Alina Szapocznikow’s mouths.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== The valorization of sacrifice as a sacred act opposed to the commodification of Enlightenment rationality is not a neutral political act ~-~- rather it is both complicit with and sanitizes the historical legacy of primordial revenge-fantasies enacted through public acts of capital punishment such as executions and lynchings. The 1ac grants the state an alibi to manufacture consent for gratuitous bloodshet ~-~- even if this disrupts the ennui of rationality it is a brutally savage form of politics that colorblindly reinforces white supremacy ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**__Lacquer wk__** Thomas, &amp;#34;Festival of Punishment&amp;#34; London Review of Books

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
http:~/~/www.lrb.co.uk/v22/n19/thomas-laqueur/festival-of-punishment

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**~ **

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)One has to infer the arguments put by the other side, or look elsewhere (to Louis Masur’s 1989 //Rites of Execution//, for example). (%%)__There (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)we will find those who have been less sanguine about human progress and the efficacy of social reform, those who think (%%)that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)punishment ought to reflect a divine and intuitively obvious (%%)moral (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)order(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Human depravity, on this view, makes it necessary for civil government to assume the power of divine authority. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Liberty__(%%)__, inalienable individual (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)rights, procedural correctness and hopes for (%%)reformation or (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)redemption have to be balanced against (%%)obligation, against (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)the needs of a righteous community, and against the feeling that, social contract or no social contract, for civil government to be legitimate it has somehow to be congruent with God’s governance. In other words, a government here on earth can cast out and kill (%%)certain of its citizens under certain circumstances (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)because God (%%)in heaven (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)has ordained (%%)that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)this (%%)should be so. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Capital punishment is the expression of both divine and communal outrage(%%) at those who have excluded themselves from full humanity through their acts.__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Although this view was not articulated in defences of the death penalty after the early 19th century, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__capital punishment retains__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)something of (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__its primordial sacrificial logic__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Killing an offender is felt to make the world safer, more as it should be, for the good people, even if no connection is made, or claimed, at the level of social policy between the act and its putative effects. (%%)__Seen in this way, as a ritual reassertion of a communal moral order, the death penalty has little to do with ideas of punishment in the rationalist Enlightenment or progressive theological traditions__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). This clash of world views, which has informed the American debate since colonial times, resounds still in books like McFeely’s. The poignant stories he tells, of three men who committed terrible crimes, of their defenders, their victims and of the criminal justice system, are embedded in a twisted past and in very different visions of how a new world is to be made. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__One of the many strengths of his __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__elegant, humane and subtle __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__book is to show how the claims and counterclaims __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__that are so __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__often made like points in a college debate – a ‘pro’ parry met by an ‘anti’ retort – are freighted with the burdens of history and the ironies of modernity. In the United States no burden is heavier than that of race__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). McFeely became involved with the question of the death penalty not because of any expertise in criminology – he had none – but because he had written a biography of Frederick Douglass and a book about the 67 descendants of a slave who had been brought to the tiny barrier island of Sapelo in 1802, where they still live today. Stephen Bright, the indefatigable and brilliant lead counsel of the Southern Center for Human Rights, wanted to make use of McFeely’s expertise in African American history. Specifically, Bright asked him to testify in support of two claims which he was making in a motion for a new trial. Bright’s client is – the case is not yet resolved – Carzell Moore, a black man convicted, along with an accomplice, of the rape and murder of a 23-year-old white convenience store clerk. He is awaiting execution. Bright planned to argue, first, that under the terms of the 14th Amendment a black man is not ‘equally protected’ in a Georgia courtroom which, like all the others in the state, displays the Confederate battle flag. And second, that there is an intimate connection between that flag and the bitter history of lynching which underscores the death sentence of any black man in the United States, particularly in the South. In some abstract sense, the flag might represent a proud tradition of states’ rights and benign local tradition, as its defenders in South Carolina have recently claimed. But in fact, as McFeely testified, the Georgia story is unambiguous. On 6 February 1956, its Governor vowed that no Negro child would ever attend school with a white one; three days later, the legislature voted to replace the Confederate horizontal bars that had graced the state flag since 1879 with the ‘stars and bars’: the blue and white cross of St Andrew on an in-your-face field of bright red. Its Civil War service done, this banner had rallied the Ku Klux Klan as it helped re-establish white power in the South during a half-century reign of terror. When, in 1993, the then Georgia Governor asked the legislature to remove this none to0 subtle exhibition of ‘pride in the enslavement of many of our ancestors’ he was jeered at, and finally withdrew his proposal after some months of hopeless advocacy. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__There have been 460 lynchings in Georgia since the late 19th century__(%%)__; 411 were of blacks. And, as Bright went on to argue in court, the surge in judicial executions after lynching declined in the 1930s could plausibly be interpreted as the swift removal of a black man by trial, which before had been effected by mob. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The cries of ‘burn ‘em’ heard as a murder suspect is booked today echo the cries of those festive crowds that attended the hangings, immolations and castrations of earlier years(%%).__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The prosecutor who opposed Bright’s motion for retrial responded – correctly, in a narrow sense – that this was all quite irrelevant. These facts had no particularly bearing on Carzell Moore; no one was proposing that he be lynched. (I also think that the three white men – die-hard segregationists all – who testified at Bright’s behest that they had celebrated the execution of Moore’s accomplice would have ‘rejoiced’ just as exuberantly at the execution of a white man. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__The festivities at the notorious serial killer Ted Bundy’s execution were replete with tailgate __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__beer __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__parties __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__and baseball caps emblazoned with the hindquarters of a pig, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__as if __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__today’s __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__Floridans had read historians’ descriptions of pre-modern carnivalesque inversion.) That said, capital punishment __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__in the United States __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__subsists __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:14.0pt&amp;#34; %)__– __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 14pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__inescapably – in a miasma of race. __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)The Honorable John H. Land in 1977 presided over the trial of a black man called William Brooks, whose case McFeely follows. Land is the son of a prominent local dignitary who had seen to the lynching of an adolescent boy 65 years earlier. The barefoot ‘little black nigger’ in question had, miraculously, escaped a murder conviction in the accidental shooting of a white boy. T.Z. Cotton – the white press and courts of his day never managed to get his name right – was kidnapped from the same Muscogee County Courthouse where Brooks was tried, taken to the edge of town and, begging for his life, pumped full of bullets. Brewster Land, Judge Land’s father, was acquitted; none of those who witnessed the abduction and murder would come forward. Forty-four years later, in 1956, a prominent black physician and civil rights leader in the same Georgia town was murdered in the course of a political confrontation: an all-white grand jury refused to indict the white man who shot him – self-defence. Even if, as is clearly the case, the murder trial of Brooks was not a lynching, the distinction is lost on many. (%%)__The power of the white establishment to maintain the social order through the death of black men is all too evident.__</headline></objectSummary><objectSummary><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/object" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Michigan/pages/Allen-Pappas%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/20"/><link rel="http://www.xwiki.org/rel/properties" href="http://opencaselist.paperlessdebate.com/xwiki/rest/wikis/opencaselist/spaces/Michigan/pages/Allen-Pappas%20Neg/objects/Admin.EntryClass/20/properties"/><id>opencaselist:Michigan.Allen-Pappas Neg:ad32b495-f2f5-44b1-8cf9-51eb2457bec7</id><guid>ad32b495-f2f5-44b1-8cf9-51eb2457bec7</guid><pageId>opencaselist:Michigan.Allen-Pappas Neg</pageId><wiki>opencaselist</wiki><space>Michigan</space><pageName>Allen-Pappas Neg</pageName><className>Admin.EntryClass</className><number>20</number><headline>==== __Specific, limited resolutions__ ensure mutual ground which is key to sustainable controversy without sacrificing creativity or openness ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Steinberg and Freeley 8** *Austin J. Freeley is a Boston based attorney who focuses on criminal, personal injury and civil rights law, AND ~*~*David L. Steinberg , Lecturer of Communication Studies @ U Miami, Argumentation and Debate: Critical Thinking for Reasoned Decision Making pp45-

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Debate is a means of settling(%%)// differences//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)so there (%%)//must be a//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) difference of opinion or a (%%)//conflict of interest//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) before there can be a debate. (%%)//If everyone is in agreement//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) on a tact or value or policy, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)there is (%%)//no need for debate//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %): (% style=&amp;#34;border: none; border: none&amp;#34; %)//the matter can be settled by unanimous co//(% style=&amp;#34;border: none; border: none; border: none&amp;#34; %)//nsent//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Thus, for example, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it would be pointless (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)to attempt (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)to debate &amp;#34;Resolved:(%%) That (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)two plus two equals four(%%),&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) because there is simply no controversy about this statement. ((% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Controversy is an essential prerequisite(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of debate. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Where there is no clash of ideas(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), proposals, interests, or expressed positions on issues, (%%)//there is no debate//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). In addition, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate (%%)//cannot produce //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)effective (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)decisions without (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)clear identification of a question or questions to be answered(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). For example, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleEmphasisEvidenceMinimizedminimizedHighlightedtag2Size1&amp;#34; %)general argument may occur about the (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)**broad topic**(%%)// of illegal //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)immigration. How many(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) illegal immigrants (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)are in the United States?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) What is the impact of illegal immigration and immigrants on our economy? What is their impact on our communities? Do they commit crimes? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Do they take job(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)s(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) from American workers? Do they pay taxes? Do they require social services? Is it a problem that some do not speak English? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Is it the responsibility of employers to discourage illegal immigration(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) by not hiring undocumented workers? Should they have the opportunity- to gain citizenship? Docs illegal immigration pose a security threat to our country? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Do illegal immigrants do work that American workers are unwilling to do?(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Are their rights as workers and as human beings at risk due to their status? Are they abused by employers, law enforcement, housing, and businesses? I low are their families impacted by their status? What is the moral and philosophical obligation of a nation state to maintain its borders? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Should we build a wall on the Mexican border(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), establish a national identification can!, or enforce existing laws against employers? Should we invite immigrants to become U.S. citizens? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Surely (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)you can think of many(%%) more (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)concerns(%%) to be addressed by a conversation about the topic area of illegal immigration. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Participation in this (%%)&amp;#34;debate&amp;#34; is likely to be emotional and intense. However, it (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is (%%)//not likely to be productive or useful without focus on //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleEmphasisEvidenceMinimizedminimizedHighlightedtag2Size1&amp;#34; %)a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBox12ptBold&amp;#34; %)particular question(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and identification of a line (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBox12ptBold&amp;#34; %)demarcating sides(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %) in the controversy(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). To be discussed and resolved effectively, (%%)//controversies must be stated clearly//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)**Vague understanding**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)results in (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)unfocused deliberation(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) and (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)poor decisions(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), frustration, and emotional distress, as (%%)//evidenced by the failure of the United States Congress to make progress on the immigration debate during the summer of 2007//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Someone disturbed by the problem of the growing underclass of poorly educated, socially disenfranchised youths might observe, &amp;#34;Public schools are doing a terrible job!(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) They are overcrowded, and many teachers are poorly qualified in their subject areas. Even the best teachers can do little more than struggle to maintain order in their classrooms.&amp;#34; That same concerned citizen, facing a complex range of issues, might arrive at an unhelpful decision, such as &amp;#34;We ought to do something about this&amp;#34; or. worse. &amp;#34;It&amp;#39;s too complicated a problem to deal with.&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Groups of concerned citizens worried about the state of public education could join together to express their frustrations(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %), anger, disillusionment, and emotions regarding the schools, (%%)//but //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)without a focus(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %) for their discussions(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)they could(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) easily (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)agree about the sorry state of education (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)**without **finding points of clarity or potential (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)solutions. A gripe(%%)// session would follow//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)But if a (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)precise question(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) is posed(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)—such as &amp;#34;What can be done to improve public education?&amp;#34;—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)then (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)a more (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)profitable area of discussion(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) is opened (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)up(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)simply by placing a focus on the search(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) for a concrete solution step(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)One or more judgments can be phrased in the form of debate propositions, motions for parliamentary debate, or bills for legislative assemblies.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The statements &amp;#34;Resolved: That the federal government should implement a program of charter schools in at-risk communities&amp;#34; and &amp;#34;Resolved: That the state of Florida should adopt a school voucher program&amp;#34; more clearly identify specific ways of dealing with educational problems in a manageable form, suitable for debate. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)They (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)provide specific policies to be investigated and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)aid (%%)discussants (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)in identifying points of difference.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)To have a (%%)//productive debate, which facilitates //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBox12pt&amp;#34; %)effective decision making(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)by(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) directing and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBox12pt&amp;#34; %)placing limits on the decision(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to be made, (%%)//the basis for argument should be clearly defined//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)If we merely talk about &amp;#34;homelessness&amp;#34; or &amp;#34;abortion&amp;#34; or &amp;#34;crime&amp;#39;* or &amp;#34;global warming&amp;#34; we are likely to have an interesting discussion but not to establish profitable basis for argument(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). For example, (%%)//the statement &amp;#34;Resolved: That the pen is mightier than the sword&amp;#34; is //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleEmphasisEvidenceMinimizedminimizedHighlightedtag2Size1&amp;#34; %)debatable, yet fails to provide much basis for clear argumentation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). If we take this statement to mean that the written word is more effective than physical force for some purposes, we can identify a problem area: the comparative effectiveness of writing or physical force for a specific purpose.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Although we now have (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a (%%)//general subject//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), we have not yet stated a problem. (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)It is still too broad(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), too loosely worded to promote well-organized argument. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)What sort of writing are we concerned with(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)—poems, novels, government documents, website development, advertising, or what? (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)What does &amp;#34;effectiveness&amp;#34; mean(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in this context? What kind of physical force is being compared—fists, dueling swords, bazookas, nuclear weapons, or what? A more specific question might be. &amp;#34;Would a mutual defense treaty or a visit by our fleet be more effective in assuring Liurania of our support in a certain crisis?&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The basis for (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)argument could be phrased in a (%%)//debate //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)proposition (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)such as &amp;#34;Resolved(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %): That (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the United States should enter into a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)mutual defense (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)treatv (%%)with Laurania.&amp;#34; (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Neg(%%)ative advocates (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)might oppose (%%)this proposition (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)by arguing(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that fleet maneuvers would be (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a better solution. This(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %) is not to say that debates should completely avoid creative interpretation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of the controversy by advocates, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)or(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)//that good debates cannot occur over //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)competing interpretations of the controversy(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %); in fact, (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)these sorts of debates may be very engaging(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %). The point is that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate is best facilitated by (%%)the guidance provided by (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)**focus on a particular point of difference**(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), which will be outlined in the following discussion.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Competition through __fair play__ is a dialogical process that encourages argumentative testing and mutual recognition of personhood ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Rawls 58** – a leading figure in moral and political philosophy (John, Justice as Fairness, Philosophical Review, April, JSTOR)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Similarly, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the acceptance of the duty of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fair play (%%)by participants in a common practice(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) is a (%%)reflection in each person of the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)recognition of the aspirations and interests of (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)others (%%)to be (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)realized by their joint activity(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Failing a special explanation, (%%)their acceptance of it is a necessary part of the criterion for their recognizing one another as persons with similar interests and capacities(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), as the conception of their relations in the general position supposes them to be. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Otherwise they would(%%) show no recognition of one another as persons with similar capacities and interests(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), and indeed, in some cases perhaps hypothetical, (%%)they would (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)not recognize one another as persons (%%)at all, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)but as (%%)complicated(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) objects (%%)involved(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) in a complicated activity. To recognize another (%%)as a person (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)one must respond(%%) to him and act towards him (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in(%%) certain ways; and these (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)ways(%%) are intimately (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)connected with the (%%)various(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) prima facie duties(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Acknowledging these duties in some degree, and so having the elements of morality, is not a matter of choice, or of intuiting moral qualities, or a matter of the expression of feelings or attitudes (the three interpretations between which philosophical opinion frequently oscillates); it is simply the possession of one of the forms of conduct in which the recognition of others as persons is manifested. These remarks are unhappily obscure. Their main purpose here, however, is to forestall, together with the remarks in Section 4, the misinterpretation that, on the view presented, (%%)the acceptance of justice and the acknowledgment of the duty of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fair play depends(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in every day life solely (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)on (%%)there being (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a de facto balance of forces (%%)between(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the (%%)parties(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). (%%)It would indeed be foolish to underestimate the importance of such a balance in securing justice(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %); but it is not the only basis thereof. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)The recognition of (%%)one another as (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)persons (%%)with similar interests and capacities engaged (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)in a common practice must(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) failing a special explanation, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)show itself in (%%)the acceptance of the principles of justice and the acknowledgment of the duty of(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) fair play(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Topical fairness requirements are key to __effective__ dialogue—monopolizing strategy and prep makes the discussion one-sided and __subverts any meaningful neg role__ ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Galloway 7** – professor of communications at Samford University (Ryan, “Dinner And Conversation At The Argumentative Table: Reconceptualizing Debate As An Argumentative Dialogue”, Contemporary Argumentation and Debate, Vol. 28 (2007), ebsco)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Debate as a dialogue __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)sets an argumentative table, where all parties receive a relatively fair opportunity to voice their position. Anything that fails to allow participants to have their position articulated denies one side of the argumentative table a fair hearing. (%%)__The affirmative side (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is set by (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)topic (%%)and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fairness requirements(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). While affirmative teams have recently resisted affirming the topic, in fact, the topic selection process is rigorous, taking the relative ground of each topic as its central point of departure.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)__Setting the affirmative reciprocally sets the negative__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). The negative crafts approaches to the topic consistent with affirmative demands. The negative crafts disadvantages, counter-plans, and critical arguments premised on the arguments that the topic allows for the affirmative team. According to fairness norms, each side sits at a relatively balanced argumentative table.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__When __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)one side takes more than its share,(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)competitive equity suffers(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). (%%)__However, it also undermines the respect due to the other involved in the dialogue. When one side excludes the other, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)fundamentally (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)denies the personhood of the other participant(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Ehninger, 1970, p. 110). (%%)__A pedagogy of debate as dialogue takes (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)this(%%) respect as a fundamental component. A desire to be fair(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) is a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)fundamental condition of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)dialogue(%%) __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that takes the form of a demand for equality of voice. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__Far from__**__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)being(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)**a banal request for links**(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)to a disadvantage, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fairness (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)is a demand for respect(%%), a demand to be heard, a demand that a voice (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)backed by(%%) literally months upon (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**months of preparation**(%%), research, and critical thinking(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)not be silenced(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)__Affirmative (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)cases that suspend (%%)basic (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fairness(%%) norms (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)**operate to exclude** particular(%%) negative (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)strategies(%%). Unprepared, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)one side comes(%%) to the argumentative table (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)unable to meaningfully participate (%%)in a dialogue.__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)__They are unable to “understand what ‘went on…’” and are left to the whims of time and power__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Farrell, 1985, p. 114). Hugh Duncan furthers this line of reasoning:(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (%%)__Opponents not only tolerate but honor and respect each other because in doing so they enhance their own chances of thinking better and reaching sound decisions__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-style:italic&amp;#34; %). Opposition is necessary because it sharpens thought in action. We assume that argument, discussion, and talk, among free an informed people who subordinate decisions of any kind, because (%%)__it is only through such discussion that we reach agreement which binds us to a common cause…If we are to be equal…relationships among equals must find expression in many formal and informal institutions__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-style:italic&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Duncan, 1993, p. 196-197).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__Debate compensates for the exigencies of the world by offering a framework that maintains equality for the sake of the conversation__**(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Farrell, 1985, p. 114).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)¶(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) For example, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__a__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)n affirmative(%%)__ (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)case(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) on the 2007-2008 college topic (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__might defend neither state nor__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)international (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__action __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)in the Middle East, and(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)__ yet claim to be germane to the topic __(%%)__in some way. The case essentially denies the arguments that state action is oppressive or that actions __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)in the international arena (%%)__are philosophically or pragmatically suspect. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Instead of allowing (%%)for (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the (%%)dialogue to be modified by the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)interchange(%%) of the affirmative case and the negative response,(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) the aff(%%)irmative (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)subverts any meaningful role to the neg(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)ative team(%%), preventing them from offering effective “counter-word” and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)undermining the value of (%%)a meaningful (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)exchange(%%) of speech acts. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**Germaneness and other substitutes **(%%)**for topical action (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)do not accrue the dialogical benefits(%%)** of topical advocacy__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Fairness is key to fun—and that’s a good thing ====

(% class=&amp;#34;SmallText&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Marc (%%)**Prensky**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), (%%)**2001**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Internationally acclaimed speaker, writer, consultant, and designer in the critical areas of education and learning, Founder, CEO and Creative Director of games2train.com, former vice president at the global financial firm Bankers Trust, BA from Oberlin College, an MBA from Harvard Business School with distinction and master&amp;#39;s degrees from Middlebury and Yale. “Fun, Play and (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)Games: What Makes Games Engaging(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %),”Digital Game-Based Learning, (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)www.marcprensky.com/writing/Prensky%20-%20Digital%20Game-Based%20Learning-Ch5.pd(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)f.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;SmallText&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)So (%%)__fun__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %) — in the sense of enjoyment and pleasure — (%%)__puts us in a relaxed, receptive frame of mind for learning__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %). Play, in addition to providing pleasure, increases our involvement, which also helps us learn.   (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Both “fun” and “play” however, have the disadvantage of being somewhat abstract, unstructured__(%%)__, and hard-to-define concepts. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)But there exists a more formal and structured way to harness(%%) (and unleash) all the power of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fun(%%) and play (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in the learning process(%%) — the powerful institution of games__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %). Before we look specifically at how we can combine games with learning, let us examine games themselves in some detail.  Like fun and play, game is a word of many meanings and implications. How can we define a game? Is there any useful distinction between fun, play and games? What makes games engaging? How do we design them?  Games are a subset of both play and fun. In programming jargon they are a “child”, inheriting all the characteristics of the “parents.” They therefore carry both the good and the bad of both terms. Games, as we will see, also have some special qualities, which make them particularly appropriate and well suited for learning.   So what is a game?  Like play, game, has a wide variety of meanings, some positive, some negative. On the negative side there is mocking and jesting, illegal and shady activity such as a con game, as well as the “fun and games” that we saw earlier. As noted, these can be sources of resistance to Digital Game-Based Learning — “we are not playing games here.” But much of that is semantic. What we are interested in here are the meanings that revolve around the definition of games involving rules, contest, rivalry and struggle.    (%%)__What Makes a Game a Game? __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)Six Structural Factors  The Encyclopedia Britannica provides the following diagram of the relation between play and games: 35 PLAY  spontaneous play    organized play (GAMES)         noncompetitive games   (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size: 9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__competitive games__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %) (CONTESTS) (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__intellectual contests__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)   physical contests (SPORTS)   Our goal here is to understand why games engage us, drawing us in often in spite of ourselves.  This powerful force stems first from the fact that they are a form of fun and play, and second from what I call the six key structural elements of games:  1. Rules 2. Goals and Objectives 3. Outcomes and Feedback 4. Conflict/Competition/Challenge/Opposition  5. Interaction, and 6. Representation or Story.   There are thousands, perhaps millions of different games, but all contain most, if not all, these powerful factors. Those that don’t contain all the factors are still classified as games by many, but can also belong to other subclasses described below. In addition to these structural factors, there are also important design elements that add to engagement and distinguish a really good game from a poor or mediocre one. Let us discuss these six factors in detail and show how and why they lead to such strong engagement.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:TimesNewRomanPSMT;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Rules are what differentiate games from other kinds of play__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %)__. __(% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size: 9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Probably the most basic definition of a game is that it is organized play, that is to say rule-based__(%%)__. If you don’t have rules you have free play, not a game__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %). Why are rules so important to games? (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Rules impose limits __(%%)__– they force us to take specific paths to reach goals and ensure that all players take the same paths__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %). They put us inside the game world, by letting us know what is in and out of bounds. (%%)__What spoils a game is not so much the cheater, who accepts the rules but doesn’t play by them__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %) (we can deal with him or her) (%%)__but the nihilist, who denies them altogether. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Rules make things both fair and exciting(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %). (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)When the Australians “bent” the rules of the America’s Cup and built a huge boat in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %) 1988(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %), and the Americans found a way to compete with a catamaran, (% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-size: 9.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__it was still a race — but no longer the same game__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-language:EN-US&amp;#34; %).

====   ====

==== Game spaces like debate are distinct from other forms of education and public speaking.  There has to be a balance of ground or else one side claims the moral high ground and creates a de facto monologue ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Hanghoj 2008** – PhD, assistant professor, School of Education, University of Aarhus, also affiliated with the Danish Research Centre on Education and Advanced Media Materials, located at the Institute of Literature, Media and Cultural Studies at the University of Southern Denmark (Thorkild, http:~/~/static.sdu.dk/mediafiles/Files/Information_til/Studerende_ved_SDU/Din_uddannelse/phd_hum/afhandlinger/2009/ThorkilHanghoej.pdf)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Debate games are often based on pre-designed scenarios(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that include descriptions of issues to be debated, educational goals, game goals, roles, rules, time frames etc. In this way, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate games differ from (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)textbooks and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)everyday classroom instruction(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)as debate scenarios allow (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)teachers and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)students to actively imagine, (%%)interact (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and communicate (%%)with(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in a (%%)domain-(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)specific game space(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) However, instead of mystifying debate games as a “magic circle” (Huizinga, 1950), I will try to overcome the epistemological dichotomy between “gaming” and “teaching” that tends to dominate discussions of educational games. In short, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)educational gaming is a form of teaching(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). As mentioned, education and games represent two different semiotic domains that both embody the three faces of knowledge: assertions, modes of representation and social forms of organisation (Gee, 2003; Barth, 2002; cf. chapter 2). In order to understand the interplay between these different domains and their interrelated knowledge forms, I will draw attention to a central assumption in Bakhtin’s dialogical philosophy. According to Bakhtin, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)all forms of communication and culture are subject to centripetal and centrifugal forces(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Bakhtin, 1981). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)A centripetal force is the drive to impose one(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) version of the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)truth(%%), while (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a centrifugal force involves a range of(%%) possible truths and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)interpretations(%%).(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) This means that any form of expression involves a duality of centripetal and centrifugal forces: “Every concrete utterance of a speaking subject serves as a point where centrifugal as well as centripetal forces are brought to bear” (Bakhtin, 1981: 272). If we take teaching as an example, it is always affected by centripetal and centrifugal forces in the on-going negotiation of “truths” between teachers and students. In the words of Bakhtin: “Truth is not born nor is it to be found inside the head of an individual person, it is born between people collectively searching for truth, in the process of their dialogic interaction” (Bakhtin, 1984a: 110). Similarly, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)dialogical (%%)space of (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate games also embodies centrifugal and centripetal forces(%%). Thus, the election scenario of The Power Game involves (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)centripetal elements(%%) that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)are mainly(%%) determined by the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)rules(%%) and outcomes of the game(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %), i.e. the election is based on a limited time frame and a fixed voting procedure. Similarly, the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)open(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)-ended (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)goals(%%), roles and resources (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)represent centrifugal elements and create (%%)virtually (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)endless possibilities for researching(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) preparing, presenting, debating and evaluating a variety of key political issues. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Consequently, the actual process of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)enacting a game scenario involves a complex negotiation between these(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) centrifugal/centripetal (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)forces(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that are inextricably linked with the teachers and students’ game activities. In this way, the enactment of The Power Game is a form of teaching that combines different pedagogical practices (i.e. group work, web quests, student presentations) and learning resources (i.e. websites, handouts, spoken language) within the interpretive frame of the election scenario. Obviously, tensions may arise if there is too much divergence between educational goals and game goals. This means that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)game facilitation requires a balance (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)between focusing too narrowly on the rules(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) or “facts” of a game (centripetal orientation) (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and a focusing too broadly on the contingent possibilities and interpretations of the game scenario (centrifugal orientation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)). For Bakhtin, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the duality(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of centripetal/centrifugal forces (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)often manifests itself as a dynamic between “monological” and “dialogical” forms of discourse(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Bakhtin illustrates this point (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)with (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)monological discourse (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of the Socrates/Plato dialogues(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in which (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**the teacher never learns anything new**(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) from the students(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), despite Socrates’ ideological claims to the contrary (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(Bakhtin, 1984a). Thus, (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)discourse becomes monologised when “someone who (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)knows(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)possesses the truth (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**instructs someone**(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)who is (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)ignorant(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)of it (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and in error(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)”, where “a thought is either affirmed or repudiated” by the authority of the teacher (Bakhtin, 1984a: 81). In contrast to this, dialogical pedagogy fosters inclusive learning environments that are able to expand upon students’ existing knowledge and collaborative construction of “truths” (Dysthe, 1996). At this point, I should clarify that Bakhtin’s term “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)dialogic” is(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) both(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)descriptive(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) term ((% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)all utterances are per definition dialogic (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)as they address other utterances as parts of a chain of communication) (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)a normative(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial&amp;#34; %)term as(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) dialogue is an (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)ideal(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to be worked for (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)against(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the forces of “(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size: 10pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 12pt; background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)monologism(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Lillis, 2003: 197-8). In this project, I am mainly interested in describing the dialogical space of debate games. At the same time, I agree with Wegerif that (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)“one of the goals of education, perhaps the most important goal, should be dialogue as an end in itself(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)” (Wegerif, 2006: 61).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Scenario simulation lets students test decisions and strategies without the real stakes of having to implement them—this __process__ is more transformative than the __content__ of the 1ac ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Hanghoj 2008** – PhD, assistant professor, School of Education, University of Aarhus, also affiliated with the Danish Research Centre on Education and Advanced Media Materials, located at the Institute of Literature, Media and Cultural Studies at the University of Southern Denmark (Thorkild, http:~/~/static.sdu.dk/mediafiles/Files/Information_til/Studerende_ved_SDU/Din_uddannelse/phd_hum/afhandlinger/2009/ThorkilHanghoej.pdf)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Joas’ re-interpretation of Dewey’s pragmatism as a “theory of situated creativity” raises a critique of humans as purely rational agents that navigate instrumentally through meansends- schemes (Joas, 1996: 133f). This critique is particularly important when trying to understand how (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)games(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)are enacted and validated (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)with(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the realm of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)educational institutions(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that by definition are inscribed in the great modernistic narrative of “progress” where nation states, teachers and parents expect students to acquire specific skills and competencies (Popkewitz, 1998; cf. chapter 3). However, as Dewey argues, the actual doings of educational gaming (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)cannot be reduced to rational means-ends schemes. (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Instead, the situated interaction between teachers, students, and learning resources are played out as contingent re-distributions of means, ends and ends in view, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)which (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)often make classroom contexts seem “messy” (%%)from an outsider’s perspective(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Barab and Squire, 2004). 4.2.3. (% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Dramatic rehearsal(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) The two preceding sections discussed how Dewey views play as an imaginative activity of educational value, and how his assumptions on creativity and playful actions represent a critique of rational means-end schemes. For now, I will turn to Dewey’s concept of dramatic rehearsal, which assumes that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)social actors deliberate by (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)projecting and(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) choosing between (%%)various (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)scenarios (%%)for future action.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Dewey uses the concept dramatic rehearsal several times in his work but presents the most extensive elaboration in Human Nature and Conduct: (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Deliberation is a dramatic rehearsal(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (in imagination) of (%%)various (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)competing (%%)possible (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)lines of action(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)… It is an experiment in finding out what the various lines of possible action are really like (...) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Thought runs ahead and foresees outcomes, and thereby avoids having to await the instruction of actual failure(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and disaster. An act overtly tried out is irrevocable, its consequences cannot be blotted out. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)An act tried out in imagination is not final (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)or fatal. It is retrievable(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Dewey, 1922: 132-3). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)This excerpt illustrates how Dewey views the process of decision making (deliberation) through the lens of an imaginative drama metaphor. Thus, decisions are made through the imag(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)inative projection of outcomes, where the “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)possible (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)competing lines of action” are resolved through a thought experiment(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Moreover, Dewey’s compelling use of the drama metaphor also implies that decisions cannot be reduced to utilitarian, rational or mechanical exercises, but that they have emotional, creative and personal qualities as well. Interestingly, there are relatively few discussions within the vast research literature on Dewey of his concept of dramatic rehearsal. A notable exception is the phenomenologist A(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial&amp;#34; %)lfred (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Schütz,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial&amp;#34; %) who (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)praises Dewey’s concept as a “fortunate image” for understanding everyday rationality(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Schütz, 1943: 140). Other attempts are primarily related to overall discussions on moral or ethical deliberation (Caspary, 1991, 2000, 2006; Fesmire, 1995, 2003; Rönssön, 2003; McVea, 2006). As Fesmire points out, dramatic rehearsal is intended to describe an important phase of deliberation that does not characterise the whole process of making moral decisions, which includes “duties and contractual obligations, short and long-term consequences, traits of character to be affected, and rights” (Fesmire, 2003: 70). Instead, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)dramatic rehearsal should be seen as the process of “crystallizing possibilities and transforming them into(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) directive (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)hypotheses”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (Fesmire, 2003: 70). Thus, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)deliberation can in no way guarantee(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the response of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a “thought experiment” will be successful(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). But (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)what (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it can(%%) do is (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)make the process of choosing more intelligent(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) than would be the case with “blind” trial-and-error (Biesta, 2006: 8). The notion of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)dramatic rehearsal provides a valuable perspective for understanding educational gaming as(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) a simultaneously (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)real and imagined inquiry into domain-specific scenarios.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Dewey defines dramatic rehearsal as the capacity to stage and evaluate “acts”, which implies an “irrevocable” difference between acts that are “tried out in imagination” and acts that are “overtly tried out” with real-life consequences (Dewey, 1922: (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:Arial&amp;#34; %)132-3). (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)This (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)description shares obvious similarities with (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)games(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) as they (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)require (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)participants (%%)to inquire into and (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)resolve scenario-specific problems(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (cf. chapter 2). On the other hand, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)there is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) also (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a striking difference between moral deliberation and educational game activities in terms of the actual consequences(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that follow particular actions. Thus, when it comes to educational games, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)acts are(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) both (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)imagined and tried out, but without all the real-life consequences(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)of the(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) practices, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)knowledge forms(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and outcomes that are being simulated in the game world. Simply put, there is a difference in realism between the dramatic rehearsals of everyday life and in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)games,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) which only “play at” or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)simulate the stakes (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and risks (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)that characterise(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)serious(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)” nature of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)moral (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)deliberation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; font-family:~&amp;#34;Times New Roman~&amp;#34;,~&amp;#34;serif~&amp;#34;;color:red&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)i.e. a real-life politician trying to win a parliamentary election experiences more personal and emotional risk than students trying to win the election scenario of The Power Game. At the same time, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)lack of real-life consequences(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in educational games (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)makes it possible to design a relatively safe learning environment(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), w(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)here teachers can stage particular game scenarios to be enacted and validated for educational purposes. In this sense, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)educational games(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) are able to (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)provide a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)safe but meaningful (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)way of letting(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)teachers and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)students make mistakes(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(e.g. by giving a poor political presentation) and dramatically rehearse particular “competing possible lines of action” that are relevant to particular educational goals (Dewey, 1922: 132). Seen from this pragmatist perspective, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the educational value(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of games (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is not so much (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)a question of (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)learning facts or (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)giving the “right” answers, but more(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) a question of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)exploring (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)contingent outcomes and (%%)domain-specific (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)processes of problem-based scenarios.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== skills unique to our model like constructing 1ACs, simulating policies, and researching positions we disagree with grounds decisions in dialogical, argumentative heuristics instead of decisionistic formulas or speculation.  Takes out aff solvency and impacts ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Mitchell 2010 **– associate professor and director of graduate studies in the Department of Communication at the University of Pittsburgh (Gordon, Rhetoric and Public Affairs, 13.1, “SWITCH-SIDE DEBATING MEETS DEMAND-DRIVEN RHETORIC OF SCIENCE”)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)The watchwords for the intelligence community’s debating initiative— collaboration, critical thinking, collective awareness—resonate with key terms anchoring the study of deliberative democracy. In a major new text, John Gastil defines deliberation as a process whereby people “carefully examine a problem and arrive at a well-reasoned solution aft er a period of inclusive, respectful consideration of diverse points of view.”40 Gastil and his colleagues in organizations such as the Kettering Foundation and the National Coalition for Dialogue and Deliberation are pursuing a research program that foregrounds the democratic telos of deliberative processes. Work in this area features a blend of concrete interventions and studies of citizen empowerment.41 Notably, a key theme in (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)much(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of this (%%)//literature concerns the relationship between deliberation and debate, with the latter//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)term (%%)//often loaded with pejorative baggage//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and working as a negative foil to highlight the positive qualities of deliberation.42 “Most political discussions, however, are debates. Stories in the media turn politics into a never-ending series of contests. People get swept into taking sides; their energy goes into figuring out who or what they’re for or against,” says Kettering president David Mathews and coauthor Noelle McAfee. “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Deliberation is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)different. It is neither a partisan argument(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) where opposing sides try to win (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)nor a casual conversation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) conducted with polite civility. Public deliberation is a means by which citizens make tough choices about basic purposes and directions for their communities and their country. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)It is a way of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)reasoning(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and talking (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)together(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).”43 Mathews and McAfee’s (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)distrust of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate (%%)process (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is (%%)almost (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)paradigmatic(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)amongst theorists and practitioners of Kettering-style deliberative democracy. One conceptual mechanism for reinforcing this debate-deliberation opposition is characterization of debate as a process inimical to deliberative aims, with debaters adopting dogmatic and fixed positions that frustrate the deliberative objective of “choice work.” In this register, Emily Robertson   observes, “unlike deliberators, debaters are typically not open to the possibility of being shown wrong. . . . Debaters are not trying to find the best solution by keeping an open mind about the opponent’s point of view.”44 Similarly, founding documents from the University of Houston–Downtown’s Center for Public Deliberation state, “Public deliberation is about choice work, which is different from a dialogue or a debate. In dialogue, people oft en look to relate to each other, to understand each other, and to talk about more informal issues. In debate, there are generally two positions and people are generally looking to ‘win’ their side.”45 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Debate, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)cast(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) here (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)as (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the theoretical (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)scapegoat(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), provides a convenient, low-water benchmark for explaining how other forms of deliberative interaction better promote cooperative “choice work.” (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Kettering-inspired (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)framework (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)receives support from perversions of the(%%) debate (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)process such as vapid presidential debates and verbal pyrotechnics(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)found on Crossfire-style(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) television shows.46 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In contrast, the intelligence community’s debating initiative stands as a(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) nettlesome (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)anomaly (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)for these theoretical frameworks, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)with debate serving(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), rather than frustrating, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the ends of deliberation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). The presence of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)such an anomaly would seem to point to the wisdom of fashioning a theoretical orientation that frames the debate-deliberation connection in contingent, rather than static terms(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), with the relationship between the categories shift ing along with the various contexts in which they manifest in practice.47 Such an approach gestures toward the importance of rhetorically informed critical work on multiple levels. First, the contingency of situated practice invites analysis geared to assess, in particular cases, the extent to which debate practices enable and/ or constrain deliberative objectives. Regarding the intelligence community’s debating initiative, such an analytical perspective highlights, for example, the tight connection between the deliberative goals established by intelligence officials and the cultural technology manifest in the bridge project’s online debating applications such as Hot Grinds. An additional dimension of nuance emerging from this avenue of analysis pertains to the precise nature of the deliberative goals set by bridge. Program descriptions notably eschew Kettering-style references to democratic citizen empowerment, yet feature deliberation prominently as a key ingredient of strong intelligence tradecraft . Th is caveat is especially salient to consider when it comes to the second category of rhetorically informed critical work invited by the contingent aspect of specific debate initiatives. To grasp this   layer it is useful to appreciate how the name of the bridge project constitutes an invitation for those outside the intelligence community to participate in the analytic outreach eff ort. According to Doney, bridge “provides an environment for Analytic Outreach—a place where IC analysts can reach out to expertise elsewhere in federal, state, and local government, in academia, and industry. New communities of interest can form quickly in bridge through the ‘web of trust’ access control model—access to minds outside the intelligence community creates an analytic force multiplier.”48 This presents a moment of choice for academic scholars in a position to respond to Doney’s invitation; it is an opportunity to convert scholarly expertise into an “analytic force multiplier.” In reflexively pondering this invitation, it may be valuable for scholars to read (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Greene and Hicks’s proposition that switch-side debating should be viewed as a cultural technology(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in light of Langdon Winner’s maxim that “technological artifacts have politics.”49 In the case of bridge, politics are informed by the history of intelligence community policies and practices. Commenter Th omas Lord puts this point in high relief in a post off ered in response to a news story on the topic: “Why should this thing (‘bridge’) be? . . . Th e intelligence community on the one hand sometimes provides useful information to the military or to the civilian branches and on the other hand it is a dangerous, out of control, relic that by all external appearances is not the slightest bit reformed, other than superficially, from such excesses as became exposed in the cointelpro and mkultra hearings of the 1970s.”50 A debate scholar need not agree with Lord’s full-throated criticism of the intelligence community (he goes on to observe that it bears an alarming resemblance to organized crime) to understand that participation in the community’s Analytic Outreach program may serve the ends of deliberation, but not necessarily democracy, or even a defensible politics. Demand-driven rhetoric of science necessarily raises questions about what’s driving the demand, questions that scholars with relevant expertise would do well to ponder carefully before embracing invitations to contribute their argumentative expertise to deliberative projects. By the same token, it would be prudent to bear in mind that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the technological determinism about switch-side debate endorsed by Greene and Hicks may tend to flatten reflexive assessments regarding the wisdom of supporting a given debate initiative—as the next section illustrates, manifest differences among initiatives warrant context-sensitive judgments regarding the normative political dimensions featured in each case(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %).    Public Debates in the EPA Policy Process  The preceding analysis of U.S. intelligence community debating initiatives highlighted how analysts are challenged to navigate discursively the heteroglossia of vast amounts of diff erent kinds of data flowing through intelligence streams. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Public policy (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)planners are tested(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)in like manner (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)when they (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)attempt to (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)stitch together(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)institutional(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)arguments from various(%%) and sundry (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)inputs(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)ranging from expert testimony, to historical precedent, to public comment. Just as intelligence managers find that (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)algorithmic,(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) formal methods (%%)of analysis (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)often don’t work (%%)when it comes to the task of interpreting and synthesizing copious amounts of disparate data(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), public-policy planners encounter similar challenges.    (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In fact,(% class=&amp;#34;UnderlineBold&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)** **(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the argumentative turn(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)in public-policy planning elaborates an approach to public-policy analysis that(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)foregrounds(%%) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)deliberative interchange and critical thinking as (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)alternatives to (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)“decisionism,” the(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) formulaic (%%)application of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)“objective” decision algorithms(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to the public policy process. Stating the matter plainly, Majone suggests, “whether in written or oral form, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)argument is central in all stages of the policy process(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).” Accordingly, he notes, “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)we miss a great deal if we (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)try to (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)understand policy(%%)-making (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)solely in terms of power(%%), influence, and bargaining, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to the exclusion of debate and argument(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).”51 One can see similar rationales driving Goodwin and Davis’s EPA debating project, where debaters are invited to conduct on-site public debates covering resolutions craft ed to reflect key points of stasis in the EPA decision-making process. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)For example, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)in the 2008 Water(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Wars (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debates (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)held (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)at EPA(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)headquarters in Washington, D.C., (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)resolutions were crafted(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)to focus attention on the topic of water pollution, with one resolution focusing on downstream states’ authority to control upstream states’ discharges and sources of pollutants, and a second resolution exploring the policy merits of bottled water and toilet paper taxes as revenue sources to fund water infrastructure projects. In the first debate on interstate river pollution, the team of Seth (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Gannon and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Seungwon(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Chung(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) from (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Wake(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Forest University argued in favor of downstream state control, with the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Michigan State(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)University team of Carly (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Wunderlich(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and Garrett (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Abelkop(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) providing opposition. In the second debate on taxation policy, Kevin (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Kallmyer (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Matthew Struth from University of Mary Washington (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)defended taxes on bottled water and toilet paper,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) while their opponents from Howard University, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Dominique Scott and Jarred McKee, argued(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)against this proposal. Reflecting on the project, Goodwin noted how (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the intercollegiate (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Switch-Side Debating Meets Demand-Driven Rhetoric of Science 107 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)debaters’ ability to act as “honest brokers” in the policy arguments contributed positively to internal EPA deliberation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) on both issues.52 Davis observed that since the invited debaters “didn’t have a dog in the fight,” they were able to give voice to previously buried arguments that some EPA subject matter experts felt reticent to elucidate because of their institutional affiliations.53 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Such (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)findings are consistent(%%) with the views of policy analysts advocating the argumentative turn in policy planning(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). As Majone claims, “(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Dialectical confrontation(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) between generalists and experts (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)often (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)succeeds in bringing out unstated assumptions(%%), conflicting interpretations of the facts, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)and(%%) the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)risks(%%) posed by new projects(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).”54 Frank Fischer goes even further in this context, explicitly appropriating rhetorical scholar Charles Willard’s concept of argumentative “epistemics” to flesh out his vision for policy studies: Uncovering the epistemic dynamics of public controversies would allow for a more enlightened understanding of what is at stake in a particular dispute, making possible a sophisticated evaluation of the various viewpoints and merits of different policy options. In so doing, the differing, oft en tacitly held contextual perspectives and values could be juxtaposed; the viewpoints and demands of experts, special interest groups, and the wider public could be directly compared; and the dynamics among the participants could be scrutizined. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)This would by no means sideline or even exclude scientific assessment; it would only situate it within the framework of a more comprehensive evaluation.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)55 As Davis notes, institutional constraints present within the EPA communicative milieu can complicate eff orts to provide a full airing of all relevant arguments pertaining to a given regulatory issue. Thus, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)intercollegiate debaters can play key roles(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) in retrieving and (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)amplifying positions that might otherwise remain sedimented in (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)policy (%%)process(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). The dynamics entailed in this symbiotic relationship are underscored by deliberative planner John Forester, who observes, “If planners and public administrators are to make democratic political debate and argument possible, they will need strategically located allies to avoid being fully thwarted by the characteristic self-protecting behaviors of the planning organizations and bureaucracies within which they work.”56 Here, an institution’s need for “strategically located allies” to support deliberative practice constitutes the demand for rhetorically informed expertise, setting up what can be considered a demand-driven rhetoric of science. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)As an instance of rhetoric of science scholarship, this type of “switch-side public (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)108 Rhetoric and Public Affairs (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)debate” differs both from insular contest tournament debating, where the main focus is on the pedagogical benefit for student participants, and first-generation rhetoric of science scholarship, where critics concentrated on unmasking the rhetoricity of scientific artifacts(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) circulating in what many perceived to be purely technical spheres of knowledge production.58 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)As a form of demand-driven rhetoric of science, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)switch-side (%%)debating (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)connects (%%)directly (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)with (%%)the communication field’s performative tradition of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)argumentative engagement(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)in public controversy—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)a different route(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of theoretical grounding (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)than (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)rhetorical criticism’s tendency to locate its foundations in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the English field’s tradition of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)literary criticism and textual analysis(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).59 Given this genealogy, it is not surprising to learn how Davis’s response to the EPA’s institutional need for rhetorical expertise took the form of a public debate proposal, shaped by Davis’s dual background as a practitioner and historian of intercollegiate debate. Davis competed as an undergraduate policy debater for Howard University in the 1970s, and then went on to enjoy substantial success as coach of the Howard team in the new millennium. In an essay reviewing the broad sweep of debating history, Davis notes, “Academic debate began at least 2,400 years ago when the scholar Protagoras of Abdera (481–411 bc), known as the father of debate, conducted debates among his students in Athens.”60 As John Poulakos points out, “older” (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Sophists(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)such as Protagoras (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)taught (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Greek students the value of dissoi logoi, or (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)pulling apart complex questions by debating two sides of an issue(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %).61 The few surviving fragments of Protagoras’s work suggest that his notion of dissoi logoi stood for the principle that “two accounts logoi are present about every ‘thing,’ opposed to each other,” and further, that humans could “measure” the relative soundness of knowledge claims by engaging in give-and-take where parties would make the “weaker argument stronger” to activate the generative aspect of rhetorical practice, a key element of the Sophistical tradition.62 Following in Protagoras’s wake, Isocrates would complement this centrifugal push with the pull of synerchesthe, a centripetal exercise of “coming together” deliberatively to listen, respond, and form common social bonds.63 Isocrates incorporated Protagorean dissoi logoi into synerchesthe, a broader concept that he used flexibly to express interlocking senses of (1) inquiry, as in groups convening to search for answers to common questions through discussion;64 (2) deliberation, with interlocutors gathering in a political setting to deliberate about proposed courses of action;65 and (3) alliance formation, a form of collective action typical at festivals,66 or in the exchange of pledges that deepen social ties.67 Switch-Side Debating Meets Demand-Driven Rhetoric of Science 109 Returning once again to the Kettering-informed sharp distinction between debate and deliberation, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)one sees (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)in(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Isocratic (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)synerchesthe,(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) as well as in the EPA debating initiative, a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)fusion of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate with deliberative functions(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). Echoing a theme raised in this essay’s earlier discussion of intelligence tradecraft , such a fusion troubles categorical attempts to classify debate and deliberation as fundamentally opposed activities. Th e significance of such a finding is amplified by the frequency of attempts in the deliberative democracy literature to insist on the theoretical bifurcation of debate and deliberation as an article of theoretical faith. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Tandem analysis of(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) the EPA and intelligence community (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)debating initiatives also brings to light(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) dimensions of contrast at the third level of Isocratic synerchesthe, alliance formation. Th e intelligence community’s Analytic Outreach initiative invites largely one-way communication flowing from outside experts into the black box of classified intelligence analysis. On the contrary, the EPA debating program gestures toward a more expansive project of (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)deliberative alliance building(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). In this vein, Howard University’s participation in the 2008 EPA Water Wars debates can be seen as the harbinger of a trend by historically black colleges and universities (hbcus) to catalyze their debate programs in a strategy that evinces Davis’s dual-focus vision. On the one hand, Davis aims to recuperate Wiley College’s tradition of competitive excellence in intercollegiate debate, depicted so powerfully in the feature film The Great Debaters, by starting a wave of new debate programs housed in hbcus across the nation.68 On the other hand, Davis sees potential for these new programs to complement their competitive debate programming with participation in the EPA’s public debating initiative. Th is dual-focus vision recalls Douglas Ehninger’s and Wayne Brockriede’s vision of “total” debate programs that blend switch-side intercollegiate tournament debating with forms of public debate designed to contribute to wider communities beyond the tournament setting.69 Whereas the political telos animating Davis’s dual-focus vision certainly embraces background assumptions that Greene and Hicks would find disconcerting—notions of liberal political agency, the idea of debate using “words as weapons”70—there is little doubt that the project of pursuing environmental protection by tapping the creative energy of hbcu-leveraged dissoi logoi differs significantly from the intelligence community’s eff ort to improve its tradecraft through online digital debate programming. Such diff erence is especially evident in light of the EPA’s commitment to extend debates to public realms, with the attendant possible benefits unpacked by Jane Munksgaard and Damien Pfister: 110 Rhetoric and Public Affairs (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Having a (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)public (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debater argue against (%%)their (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)convictions(%%),(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) or confess their indecision on a subject and subsequent embrace of argument as a way to seek clarity, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)could shake (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)up (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the prevailing view of debate as a war of words. (%%)Public uptake of the possibility of switch-sides (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)debate may (%%)help (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)lessen (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)polarization (%%)of issues(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) inherent in prevailing debate formats (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)because students are no longer(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)seen (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)as (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)wedded to (%%)their (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)arguments. This could transform (%%)public (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)debate (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)from a tussle between advocates, with each public debater trying to convince the audience in a Manichean struggle about the truth of their side, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to a more inviting exchange focused on (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)content (%%)of the other’s argumentation (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and the process of deliberative exchange.71 (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Reflection on the EPA debating initiative reveals a striking convergence among (1) the expressed need for dissoi logoi by government agency officials(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) wrestling with the challenges of inverted rhetorical situations, (2) theoretical claims by scholars regarding the centrality of argumentation in the public policy process(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %), and(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (3) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the practical wherewithal of intercollegiate debaters to tailor public switch-side debating performances(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in specific ways requested by agency collaborators. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)These points of convergence(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) both underscore previously articulated theoretical assertions regarding the relationship of debate to deliberation, as well as deepen understanding of the political role of deliberation in institutional decision making. But they also (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)suggest (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)how decisions by rhetorical scholars about whether to contribute switch-side debating acumen to meet demand-driven rhetoric of science initiatives ought to involve careful reflection. Such an approach mirrors the way (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)policy planning in (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the “argumentative turn(%%)” is designed to (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)respond to (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)weaknesses of(%%) formal, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)decisionistic paradigms(%%) of policy planning (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)with (%%)situated, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)contingent judgments (%%)informed by reflective deliberation.(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) Conclusion Dilip Gaonkar’s criticism of first-generation rhetoric of science scholarship rests on a key claim regarding what he sees as the inherent “thinness” of the ancient Greek rhetorical lexicon.72 That lexicon, by virtue of the fact that it was invented primarily to teach rhetorical performance, is ill equipped in his view to support the kind of nuanced discriminations required for eff ective interpretation and critique of rhetorical texts. Although Gaonkar isolates rhetoric of science as a main target of this critique, his choice of subject matter Switch-Side Debating Meets Demand-Driven Rhetoric of Science 111 positions him to toggle back and forth between specific engagement with rhetoric of science scholarship and discussion of broader themes touching on the metatheoretical controversy over rhetoric’s proper scope as a field of inquiry (the so-called big vs. little rhetoric dispute).73 Gaonkar’s familiar refrain in both contexts is a warning about the dangers of “universalizing” or “globalizing” rhetorical inquiry, especially in attempts that “stretch” the classical Greek rhetorical vocabulary into a hermeneutic metadiscourse, one pressed into service as a master key for interpretation of any and all types of communicative artifacts. In other words, Gaonkar warns against the dangers of rhetoricians pursuing what might be called supply-side epistemology, rhetoric’s project of pushing for greater disciplinary relevance by attempting to extend its reach into far-flung areas of inquiry such as the hard sciences. Yet this essay highlights how rhetorical scholarship’s relevance can be credibly established by outsiders, who seek access to the creative energy flowing from the classical Greek rhetorical lexicon in its native mode, that is, as a tool of invention designed to spur and hone rhetorical performance. Analysis of the intelligence community and EPA debating initiatives shows how this is the case, with government agencies calling for assistance to animate rhetorical processes such as dissoi logoi (debating different sides) and synerchesthe (the performative task of coming together deliberately for the purpose of joint inquiry, collective choice-making, and renewal of communicative bonds).74 Th is demand-driven epistemology is diff erent in kind from the globalization project so roundly criticized by Gaonkar. Rather than rhetoric venturing out from its own academic home to proselytize about its epistemological universality for all knowers, instead here we have actors not formally trained in the rhetorical tradition articulating how their own deliberative objectives call for incorporation of rhetorical practice and even recruitment of “strategically located allies”75 to assist in the process. Since the productivist content in the classical Greek vocabulary serves as a critical resource for joint collaboration in this regard, demand-driven rhetoric of science turns Gaonkar’s original critique on its head. In fairness to Gaonkar, it should be stipulated that his 1993 intervention challenged the way rhetoric of science had been done to date, not the universe of ways rhetoric of science might be done in the future. And to his partial credit, Gaonkar did acknowledge the promise of a performance-oriented rhetoric of science, especially one informed by classical thinkers other than Aristotle.76 In his Ph.D. dissertation on “Aspects of Sophistic Pedagogy,” Gaonkar documents how the (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)ancient (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)sophists were (%%)“the greatest (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)champions(%%)”(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) 112 Rhetoric and Public Affairs (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)of “socially useful” science(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %),77 and also how the sophists essentially practiced the art of rhetoric in a translational, performative register: Th e sophists could not blithely go about their business of making science useful, while science itself stood still due to lack of communal support and recognition. Besides, sophistic pedagogy was becoming increasingly dependent on the findings of contemporary speculation in philosophy and science. Take for instance, the eminently practical art of rhetoric. As taught by the best of the sophists, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it was not simply a handbook (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)of recipes which (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)anyone could (%%)mechanically (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)employ to(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)his (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)advantage(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). On the contrary, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the strength (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and vitality (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)of sophistic rhetoric came from (%%)their (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)ability to incorporate (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)relevant info(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)rmation (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)obtained from (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)on-going research in other fields(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).78 Of course, deep trans-historical diff erences make uncritical appropriation of classical Greek rhetoric for contemporary use a fool’s errand. But to gauge from Robert Hariman’s recent reflections on the enduring salience of Isocrates, “timely, suitable, and eloquent (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)appropriations” can help (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)us(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) postmoderns (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)“(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)forge(%%) a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)new political language” (%%)suitable (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)for addressing (%%)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)complex (%%)raft of intertwined (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)problems(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)facing global society. Such retrospection is long overdue, says Hariman, as “the history, literature, philosophy, oratory, art, and political thought of Greece and Rome have never been more accessible or less appreciated.”79 Th is essay has explored ways that some of the most venerable elements of the ancient Greek rhetorical tradition—those dealing with (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and deliberation—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)can be retrieved(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and adapted to answer calls (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)in the contemporary milieu for cultural technologies capable of dealing with one of our time’s most daunting challenges. This(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) challenge (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)involves finding meaning in inverted rhetorical situations (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:6.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)characterized by an endemic surplus of heterogeneous content.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Argument by definition requires limits—the existence of clash in this round doesn’t mean there’s an appropriate frame of reference.  This proves ground is key—not because we’d have nothing to say, but because setting the agenda makes us negate descriptive facts or moral truisms instead of collectively reason ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Rowland 1987 **– professor of communication at the University of Kansas (Robert, Philosophy and Rhetoric, 20.3, “On defining argument”, p. 155-6, EBSCO)

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)The final two characteristics identified by Brockriede~-~-a willingness to risk confrontation and a shared frame of reference~-~-also are not necessary attributes of argument. (%%)__People often support __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)their (%%)__claims __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)with reasons and evidence (%%)__although they don&amp;#39;t share a frame of reference or risk confrontation__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). When the Soviet and United States ambassadors to the United Nations engage in debate, they support their claims, but there is no risk of self and no shared frame of reference. Thus, characteristics (5) and (6) are not essential to the definition of argument. Rather, they are essential to the successful resolution of argument. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__Without a shared frame__(%%)__ of reference__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and a willingness to risk the self, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__there is little chance of rationally resolving a dispute__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)Conclusion                                                                                                    

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__The functional approach__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to the study of argumentation (%%)__is valuable because it (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)provides a clear (%%)definition of the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)scope(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of argumentation. It recognizes that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__while all argument is rhetorical, not all rhetoric is argument__**__. One danger__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) associated with some recent work on argument (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__is__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)that the term (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__argument__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)itself (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__becomes so broad __(%%)__that (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)it loses (%%)all (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)meaning. **If argument is**(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) defined to include (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)**__all disagreement__**(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), all (%%)__comparison of__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) construct (%%)__systems, __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)and all instances in which an individual believes that he or she is arguing (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__then__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)essentially (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__all communication is argument__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
__A more useful definitional move is to treat (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)argument(%%) as the__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) symbolic (%%)__form__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)(s) we use (%%)__to solve problems__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) rationally. This implies that argument is the method of reason. Such a definition (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__sets__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)the (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__limits__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of argumentation (%%)__and defines the form of argument in relation to the function__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of arguing. Moreover, so to define argument recognizes the role of evaluation in the study of argument. (%%)__Merely to describe an argument__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) or set of arguments leaves their human significance out of consideration. Once the arguments of a speech, essay, or other verbal interaction have been described with accuracy, the next point of critical interest is naturally the arguments&amp;#39; relative quality as efforts to induce closure. (%%)__The value of (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)examining arguments is undercut if description becomes the only aim(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of criticism of argumentation. A socially satisfying definition of argument and a useful theory of argumentation must provide at least trained theorists with grounds for distinguishing between weak and strong arguments, as the functional definition does.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
__Some will__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) perhaps (%%)__object that the functional definition__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of argument for which I have contended (%%)__restricts a student__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of argumentation to study of propositional discourse. (%%)__This is true in the sense that (% style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)my definition identifies reason-giving as (%%)a (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)fundamental (%%)characteristic__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of argument, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__and__(%%)__ reason-giving (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is propositional(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). On the other hand, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__an issue__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that needs clarification in theory of argument, as I have shown, (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__is whether &amp;#34;argumentation&amp;#34;__(% style=&amp;#34;mso-bidi-font-family:Georgia;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__ and &amp;#34;rhetoric&amp;#34; are__(%%)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt; mso-bidi-font-family:Georgia&amp;#34; %)to be(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) considered (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__synonymous. If so, the concept__(%%)__ of &amp;#34;argument&amp;#34; (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)becomes unnecessary(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %); the concept of &amp;#34;rhetoric&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Georgia&amp;#34; %) is sufficient. My contention(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) is that arguments occur in rhetoric and need to be recognized, described, and evaluated in light of their unique functional and formal features. Arguments cannot be understood by applying the same kinds of analysis as we would apply if, say, rhythm were our point of interest. Arguments are formally and functionally different from rhythmic patterns, situational constraints, levels of vocabulary, and the like-all features of rhetoric. If argument is taken to be the means by which humans rationally solve problems-or try to, arguments can be identified , described, and evaluated critically as part of the broader enterprise of identifying, describing, and evaluating rhetoric. Across centuries, people have believed (%%)__there is__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) such (%%)__a process as (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)trying to arrive at(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)preferred(%%)__ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)conclusions by rational means(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %), rather than by non-rational means. (%%)__That process__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), I have argued, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)entails(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__ __(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)distinctive verbal (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)forms(% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)__ (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)appropriate to the function(%%)__(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)of the process. It is at least useful to give such purposeful forms and function a name. Traditionally and contemporaneously &amp;#34;(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)argument&amp;#34; is(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %) (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)philosophically and etymologically (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the appropriate name(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:7.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

==== Precisely defining terms is pedagogically valuable—T debates provide portable skills needed to settle all major questions ====

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
**Steinberg and Freeley 8** *Austin J. Freeley is a Boston based attorney who focuses on criminal, personal injury and civil rights law, AND ~*~*David L. Steinberg , Lecturer of Communication Studies @ U Miami, Argumentation and Debate: Critical Thinking for Reasoned Decision Making pp61-63

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
I. THE IMPORTANCE OF DEFINING TERMS

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleEmphasisEvidenceMinimizedminimizedHighlightedtag2Size1&amp;#34; %)definition of terms(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %)—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)the advocate&amp;#39;s (%%)//supported interpretation//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) of the meaning of the words in a proposition—(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background: yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)is (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)an (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)essential part(%%)// of //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)debate. (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)In some (%%)instances the opposing advocates will agree right away on the definition of terms, and the debate will move on to other issues. In other (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)cases the locus(%%) of the debate (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)may be the definition of (%%)a key term or (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight: yellow&amp;#34; %)terms, and (%%)definitions become (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)the &amp;#34;voting issue&amp;#34;(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) that decides the debate. (%%)//In //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)all debates(%%)//, however, a //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)shared understanding(%%)// of the //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)interpretation of the proposition(%%)// is //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)necessary(%%)// to //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)guide argumentation(%%)// and //(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)decision making.

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)Many intercollegiate debate propositions call for the &amp;#34;federal government&amp;#34; to adopt a certain policy. Often the term is self-evident in the context of the proposition, and no definition is necessary. In debates on the 2001-2002 CEDA proposition(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). &amp;#34;Resolved: That the United States Federal Government should substantially increase federal control throughout Indian Country in one or more of the following areas: child welfare, criminal justice, employment, environmental protection, gaming, resource management, taxation,&amp;#34; the affirmative merely designated the appropriate federal agency (for example. The bureau of Indian Affairs or the Environmental Protection Agency) to cam&amp;#39; out its policy, and the debate moved on to other issues. However, sometimes other terms in the proposition (for instance, Indian Country) become critical issues of the debate. Not infrequently the negative will raise the issue of topicality and argue that the affirmative&amp;#39;s plan is not the best definition, or interpretation, of the proposition. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In debates on propositions of value, (%%)//the clash over definitions//(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) or criteria may be (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)crucial to the outcome(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In debates (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)outside the educational setting, the same (%%)situation (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)prevails(%%). In some debates the definition of terms is easy and obvious—they need only be stated &amp;#34;for the record(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %).&amp;#34; and the debate proceeds to other issues. (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)In other debates however, the definition may be (% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %)all-important(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). For instance (%%)//physicians, clerics, and ethicists conduct long, hard-fought debates on the critical issue of when life begins//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %): At conception? When the fetus becomes capable of surviving outside the womb? When the brain begins to function? Or at the moment of birth?

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
Exactly(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %) the opposite problem arose, and continues, in debates over the use of organ transplants. Does death occur when breathing slops? (% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %)When the heart stops? Or when the brain ceases to function? Some states have debated this Issue and adopted new definitions of death; in other states the debate continues. Similarly, (%%)//environmentalists seeking protection from development//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size: 8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)for valued resources (%%)//debate the definition of wetlands//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) in public hearings; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)owners of sports franchises work to redefine players&amp;#39; salaries to fit within predetermined salary caps(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %); and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)customers considering new product purchases study competing definitions of value(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). In February 2004, President (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow; mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)Bush called (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)upon the Congress to(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) &amp;#34;promptly (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)pass(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) and send to the states (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)for(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) ratification, (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)an amendment(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) to our Constitution defining and (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)protecting marriage(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %) as a union of a man and a woman as husband and wife.&amp;#34; (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)This(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size: 12.0pt&amp;#34; %) (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)advocacy by the president was an attempt (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)to (%%)//define &amp;#34;marriage&amp;#34; in such a way as to limit it to heterosexual //(% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)couples. A public(%%)// debate about the meaning of marriage//(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %), (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)and its alternative, &amp;#34;civil union,&amp;#34; (% style=&amp;#34;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow&amp;#34; %)ensued. Definitional(% class=&amp;#34;Box&amp;#34; %) debates have political, moral, and personal implications(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %). What is poverty? Obesity? Adulthood? In 2007, the meaning of the term &amp;#34;surge&amp;#34; in reference to the United States military&amp;#39; action in Iraq was hotly contested. Was this an expansion of the war or simply provision of necessary resources to achieve existing objectives? The 2007 immigration reform offered the opportunity for illegal immigrants working in this country to achieve citizenship through a cumbersome and expensive process. The (% class=&amp;#34;StyleBoldUnderline&amp;#34; %)reform legislation failed in part because it was termed &amp;#34;amnesty&amp;#34; by its opponents. Likewise, the definition of &amp;#34;terrorism&amp;#34; creates significant problems in our foreign policy(% style=&amp;#34;font-size:8.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt&amp;#34; %).

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
 

(% class=&amp;#34;MsoNormal&amp;#34; %)
